/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/punc/punc-01603/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/punc/punc-01603/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/punc/punc-01603/canvas/1/fb9a4613-9bac-466f-a4ff-5c2a96dfae07","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2025-08-15T18:45:05.052Z","creator":"Olivia Flores","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>As Barry enters his sister’s house, he is flanked by a mirror on his right and a painting of a beach at night on his left. The mirror—another piece of glass—may represent his present inability to look clearly at himself and deal with his problems face on; instead, he acts out during moments of blind rage and resorts to lying, only coming fully clean at the end of the film when he explains to Lena what happened with the phone sex line scam. The painting will be echoed by the beachside dinner that he shares with Lena in Hawaii, the place where he is finally able to find peace. These two objects, then, externalize the emotional journey that he is setting on by meeting and pursuing Lena.</p>"}],"target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/punc/punc-01603/canvas/1#xywh=104,158,1787,435"},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/punc/punc-01603/canvas/1/7845ba8d-6d7f-49b4-9c7b-b2ff5e857804","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2025-08-15T18:45:31.092Z","creator":"Olivia Flores","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>As in critical scenes with Lena, Barry struggles with another threshold. Entering new spaces and new relationships terrifies him.</p>"}],"target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/punc/punc-01603/canvas/1#xywh=1105,609,193,200"}]}]}]}